## FLAT FILE FORMAT
The input flat file (in GCS) follows this structure:
- Each "section" starts with a HEADER record (identified by a type code in column 1-2, e.g. "H1", "H2")
- Each header is followed by N DETAIL records (identified by "D1", "D2" etc.)
- A file can contain MULTIPLE header types (e.g. H1+D1 sections and H2+D2 sections interleaved)
- File is pipe-delimited (|), UTF-8, stored in GCS

Example file layout:
  H1|ORDER_ID|CUSTOMER_ID|ORDER_DATE|TOTAL_AMOUNT
  D1|LINE_ID|PRODUCT_ID|QTY|UNIT_PRICE|DISCOUNT
  D1|LINE_ID|PRODUCT_ID|QTY|UNIT_PRICE|DISCOUNT
  H2|SHIPMENT_ID|CARRIER|SHIP_DATE|TRACKING_NO
  D2|PKG_ID|WEIGHT|DIMENSIONS|STATUS

## BIGQUERY TARGET TABLES
Map each record type to a BQ table:
  H1 → dataset.orders          (order_id, customer_id, order_date, total_amount)
  D1 → dataset.order_lines     (line_id, order_id [FK from parent H1], product_id, qty, unit_price, discount)
  H2 → dataset.shipments       (shipment_id, carrier, ship_date, tracking_no)
  D2 → dataset.packages        (pkg_id, shipment_id [FK from parent H2], weight, dimensions, status)

CRITICAL: Detail records must inherit the parent header's ID as a foreign key.

